	<title><![CDATA[Meeting with Dr. Cardonza – Understanding the Context for the Solution and Maximizing Value]]></title>
    <descriptionText><![CDATA[<Introtext style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; color:#cc0033; margin:10px; padding:0 0 0 5px; background:#e8e8e8; border-bottom:1px solid #333; display:block;">Meeting with Dr. Cardonza – Understanding the Context for the Solution and Maximizing Value</Introtext><welcomeText style=" font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:18pt; text-align:justify; font-weight:normal; color:#333; display:block; margin:0 10px 10px">"Both are big, both are important, and thankfully – they’re complementary.  The focus around patient treatment goals is primary, because if our patients do well, then everything else follows.  However, I do have concerns about patient satisfaction, mainly because it’s a softer metric and less objectively measured.  Sometimes, patients don’t want to do what’s in their own best interest – like getting up and walking around a safe time after heart surgery, or being compliant when on fluid restriction.  Providing the right care for patients could sometimes end up hurting satisfaction scores."  </welcomeText>]]></descriptionText>
